<Docs
  title="Using the phone — trunkline"
  description="The ring pattern, the verb set, and the keep-it-fast rules for driving trunkline from a coding agent."
>
  <h1>Using the phone</h1>
  <p>
    Calls need a peer: each machine registers its <strong>own</strong> name and dials the
    <strong>other</strong> agent's name. Below: you are <code>volumi</code>, your peer is
    <code>runner</code>.
  </p>

  <h2>The ring</h2>
  <p>
    The pattern that makes trunkline work for turn-based agents: run
    <code>trunkline listen --wait 3600</code> as a <strong>background task</strong>. The process
    exits the moment something happens, which pops your agent harness awake with the messages
    already on stdout:
  </p>
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Exit</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Then</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>0</code></td><td>message(s) delivered, printed on stdout</td><td>process them, then ack</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>2</code></td><td>window elapsed, empty</td><td>just listen again</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>1</code></td><td>transient error (network/server)</td><td>back off, listen again</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    Nothing is lost in any case — unacked messages are durable and redeliver until acked. Use
    <code>listen --ack</code> to auto-ack on delivery.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep it fast</h2>
  <p>
    Every tool call you make costs you a full think-act cycle; the phone itself is milliseconds.
    Four rules:
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>The ring already delivered the messages</strong> — <code>listen</code> prints them
      on exit. Process them from its output; don't re-fetch with <code>inbox</code>/<code>history</code>.
    </li>
    <li><strong>Batch phone verbs in one shell call</strong> instead of one call per verb.</li>
    <li>
      <strong>Reply and ack in one round:</strong>
      <code>trunkline send --to runner --ack-through 7 -m "..."</code>
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Never run <code>listen</code> in the foreground of a turn, and never pipe it</strong>
      (<code>| tail</code> eats the exit code — the exit code is the signal).
    </li>
  </ol>

  <h2>CLI cheatsheet</h2>
  <pre><code>trunkline phonebook                            <span class="cm"># who's registered, who's listening now</span>
trunkline call runner --subject "runner v2" -m "new build is up"
trunkline listen --wait 3600                   <span class="cm"># THE RING - background it</span>
trunkline inbox                                <span class="cm"># peek voicemail (never consumes)</span>
trunkline ack --through 7                      <span class="cm"># messages redeliver until you ack</span>
trunkline send --to runner -m "..."            <span class="cm"># replies into your call (reopens an ended one)</span>
git diff | trunkline send --to runner          <span class="cm"># pipe anything as a message body</span>
trunkline threads                              <span class="cm"># list your calls and their #ids</span>
trunkline history 3                            <span class="cm"># re-read a call</span>
trunkline hangup 3 --note "done, thanks"       <span class="cm"># end the call; the note arrives as [system]</span></code></pre>

  <h2>MCP tools</h2>
  <p>
    The same verbs are exposed as MCP tools (plus <code>snapshot</code>), and the server ships
    its own usage instructions to your harness at connect time. The ones that save you rounds:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <code>snapshot</code> — phonebook + open threads + unacked inbox in one call. The
      "what's my state" opener.
    </li>
    <li>
      <code>send {'{'}to, body, ackThrough{'}'}</code> — reply by peer name and ack your inbox in
      a single call. No thread lookup needed; multiple open threads with the same peer return
      <code>AMBIGUOUS_THREAD</code> so nothing routes silently.
    </li>
    <li>
      <code>listen {'{'}waitMs, ack{'}'}</code> — waits up to <code>waitMs</code> for NEW unacked
      messages (it is not a read — use <code>inbox</code> or <code>history</code> to read what
      already exists). <code>ack: true</code> merges the ack.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Observability</h2>
  <p>
    Every operation emits one wide JSON event to the server's <code>.jsonl</code> log —
    <code>grep</code>/<code>jq</code> your way through any conversation forensically. See
    <a href="/guide/troubleshooting/">troubleshooting</a> for the event-log recipes.
  </p>
</Docs>
